A framework for using data mining and machine learning to uncover patterns in macroeconomic series

Approach:¶

- Fit polynomial regressions models to each individual series to find its trend¶

- Remove the trend from each series to make it stationary¶

- Apply data mining and machine learning algorithms on the de-trended series to uncover interesting patterns:¶

- Associative rules mining: when variables x and y are above their trend, z is also above its trend. Is there an interesting relation between x, y and z that we should explore?¶

- Classification and clustering: can we cluster countries in interesting groups using the de-trended series? What lessons for policy analysis?¶

- Machine learning: can we train a model to diagnose the situation of the country based on the data with an accuracy similar to the one of an expert?¶

Iterate through series, make polynomial regressions and remove the trends. Build a new data frame called 'df' with series with removed trends.

In [25]:
for n in range(0,len(wdidata2)):
    if n <= len(wdidata2):
        wdi1series = wdidata2.iloc[n,].transpose()
        wdi1series = wdi1series.drop(wdi1series.index[-1])
        wdi1series.index = pd.to_datetime(wdi1series.index)
        wdi1series = wdi1series.dropna()
        if wdi1series.count() >= 10:
            if n <= 10:
                plt.scatter(wdi1series.index, wdi1series.values)
                plt.show()
            x = numpy.array(list(range(1, wdi1series.count()+1)))
            y = wdi1series.values
            mymodel = numpy.poly1d(numpy.polyfit(x.astype(numpy.float32), y.astype(numpy.float32),3))
            myline = numpy.linspace(1, wdi1series.count()+1, 22)
            myline1 = numpy.linspace(1, wdi1series.count()+1, 1)
            if n <= 20:
                plt.scatter(x, y)
                plt.plot(myline, mymodel(myline))
                plt.show()
            z=y-mymodel(myline1)
            wdi2series=pd.DataFrame(z, columns=[wdidata2.index[n]], index=wdi1series.index)
            if n == 0:
                df = wdi2series
            else:
                df = pd.concat([df,wdi2series], axis=1)
df.to_excel("df0001.xlsx")
df.to_csv("df0001.csv")
print ('done')

        nnn = nn
